    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Study of the Enterprises in Thanjavur for Micro Enterprise Loan Product</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Dineshkumar B</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Enterprises in Thanjavur<br />Enterprise Loan Product</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">May-2012 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">P5954</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">One of the most pronounced findings made in this study was that seasonality is distinct, both in theory and in application, in the sense that there is an evident difference between sales, procurement, and profit (see “Tailor” to see a truly well-constructed representation of seasonality). Another finding that was made was that location had great potential to play a role in procurement, sales, and profit, thus affective whatever working capital loan amount could be given to an enterprise. The importance of location is yet to be properly quantified, thoug.
In order that improvements be made on this project, one should make it a priority to spend more time in Thanjavur, in order to collect more data on a great variety of enterprises. Additionally, since a lot of stores either lacked seasonality data or were unwilling to present such information (see “Limitations”), a more precise, subtle questionnaire should be developed and subsequently employed. So that this can be accomplished, it would be prudent to conduct several preliminary interviews with other microenterprises in order that afterwards, an appropriate questionnaire can be developed with which to survey everyone with.
With regards to grocery stores, a deeper investigation on procurement cycles should be conducted. It was suggested that a delineation of different kinds of goods sold at such stores would be useful, such as vegetables, food items (further separating them into wet and dry items, or perishable and non-perishable goods), snacks, and cosmetic items. By separating these goods, a more detailed procurement cycle could be modeled for each shop; in fact, if it could be modeled for each good time, then, depending on what a shop stocked, a typecast could be made for the store. This method of separation could also be applied to the petty shop, hotels, and restaurants.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/11433">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/11433</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/9711">MBA-2012</a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
